Fiat said the combined business would be 50% owned by FCA shareholders and 50% owned by those of Renault. Pressure for consolidation among car makers has grown with the challenges posed by electrification, tightening emissions regulations and expensive new technologies being developed for connected and autonomous vehicles. The deal being discussed would include guarantees covering corporate governance and employment in France and Italy, the French daily said. Earlier in 2019 FCA Chairperson John Elkann a member of Italy's Agnelli dynasty that controls the company - stressed the family's commitment to the automotive industry. But he also added that they were prepared to take "bold and creative decisions" to help build a solid and attractive future for the company. --Reuters-- 